content: Such a beautiful simple calm musical intuitive problem solving journey for 3 to 4 year olds. Well done.

No offense meant to the developers, but this is not what I wanted.  I was hoping for something more like ABC Mouse, with learning exercises, puzles, stories, art, that my son could use occasionally on a long trip.  Though it's described as encouraging critical thinking and problem solving, Thinkrolls 2 is all within the narrow platform of video game indoctrination.  I see comments that others' children are already addicted to it. That's not actually a good thing, unless you just want your kid to be quiet and leave you alone.  I get that, but encouraging video gaming is not the answer.
My 4 years old loves this game and wants to play all the time.

Those must be some smart kids! My 5 year old daughter has to come to me for help from time to time and she is pretty sharp.  I highly recommend this game. Its really cute, brilliant and straightforward. Did I say no ads? :)

content: Well worth the couple of quid. Amusing, pretty and great to play along with my 3 and 5 year olds alike.
Great for learning and thinking ahead. Devs: would be really nice to have a way to reset progress back to a specific point rather than a total reset, you could show the level chooser to do this.

Another great game for kids from Avokiddo. New items to handle and new mazes. As the previous thinkrolls, the game challenges kids' abilities. 2 levels, easy n hard, so that in the time  the kid will be familiarized with all the tricky items, hard level will still keep his interesting.

My 3,5 yr old son is absolutely enthralled with this game. The game progressively becomes harder at just the right pace to keep him entertained, while not frustrated. There is no IAP nonsense, or anything that takes you out of the game to the app store (my biggest gripe with most games my toddler wants to play).  Well built app. 6 out 5 stars.

The first version of the app is great, and this follow-up is equally great, if not better. My 5 year old son played through levels for like an hour straight. It's the first time I've seen him be that determined and persistent. As a high school math teacher, I wish my current students had played these games as kids to develop logic and problem solving skills that they currently lack.
